Open Source Calculus

I've been using an open course textbook to aid my instruction of Calculus I this fall. I've also been using the open source platform MyOpenMath for student homework. MyOpenMath is quite exciting as a tool - it is flexible and user friendly. Students have also liked it though one does need to carefully check questions before assigning. Using open source tools has clearly made a difference in equitable access from the start of the semester (and hence likely to ultimate success). Given the online structure of coursework, tools like these and GeoGebra (all in the big tent of active learning) have made a positive difference in learning. As we approach the final month of the semester, I look forward to final results and written student feedback on the combination of tools and approaches under stressful conditions.

item.title: About Me
item.dc:creator: drbuske
item.content:encoded:
I am a mathematician.

This simply means I do math. And I enjoy doing math and try to relay that passion to others.

Some tidbits about me:
- I live in Sartell. I'm married and have two daughters that both work with data. No dogs. No pets of any sort.
- I enjoy music and progressive rock from the ancient past is my preferred genre.
- DIY projects keep me busy in any spare time. The "honey do" list is always longer than it should be.
- In 2007 I crushed my skull and in 2017 I broke my neck. Can't wait to see what 2027 brings.

item.title: 10 Keys To Success at St. Cloud State University
item.dc:creator: drbuske
item.content:encoded:
1. Make college a high priority.
2. Be responsible for your own learning.
3. Design a well-balanced schedule.
4. Attend classes daily.
5. Take good notes.
6. Do reading/homework daily.
7. Get to know your professors.
8. Participate in extracurricular activities.
9. Ask questions.
10. Be open to learning.

item.title: Using GeoGebra in ODEs
item.dc:creator: drbuske
item.content:encoded: This summer I taught an ODEs with Linear Algebra course. During a pandemic. Online. Lots to say about the experience, but one surprisingly useful tool was GeoGebra. Over the next few years, I suspect the tool will become even stronger. But even now it is useful in routine computations such as performing row reduction, finding eigenvalues and eigenvectors, solving first-order IVPs, solving systems, numerical solutions (of systems too!), vector field plots, investigating stability, and much more. I know it isn't the most powerful tool, but given the circumstances, it was great to have a simple tool to point students toward that works on so many platforms. Not having huge overhead (financial or logistical) is a huge plus. OERs are not going away. If you haven't used this tool or haven't used it lately, give it a try.

item.title: Oral Exams
item.dc:creator: drbuske
item.content:encoded: COVID-19 changed how we do business in higher ed. One tool I had never used before was the oral exam. While my original intent was to fill the 'proctored exam' gap in having more authentic assessment in my courses, the benefits turned out to mean far more. One important element in any classroom is connections - between instructor and students (and students and students). Being completely online made one-on-one connections a challenge. But oral exams helped in that aspect. Yes, they took a significant amount of time, but in the end, they were well worth it. I encourage my math colleagues to give it a try.
